It offers a wide range of content, created by pilots, aviation and recruitment experts: from articles and podcasts to a Resume Builder.

We could not pass the #dontrushchallenge 😁! This video features some of the women flying for Cathay Pacific👩🏻‍✈️. We are all pilots on the B777, A330, A350 or B747. During covid-19 some of us are flying a lot and go from one hotel isolation layover to the next (on the B747 🙋‍♀️), while others on the passenger fleet currently don’t get to fly a lot. We try to keep our spirit up, and together we created something so fun and so joyful :) Happy and mighty proud to be part of this group of amazing ladies. Enjoy our video ❤️
•
Watch the full video on my IGTV (turn your phone 😜) or go to Youtube and check the Cathay Pacific Ladies Don’t Rush Challenge 😄

node.text:
George in charge, on a recent flight from Frankfurt to Hong Kong ✈️ 
George is a nickname for the autopilot indeed 😉 

When can we use the autopilot on the B747-8? We are not to engage it below 200 feet above the ground; and when circumstances don’t allow for an autoland, the autopilot must be disengaged before 100 feet above the runway. However, these are the limitations; we are allowed to fly manually and engage the autopilot much later in flight, and to disengage much earlier.

All takeoffs are flown manually, and I would say over 99% of the landings are manual as well; we normally only use the autoland capability in the event of too low visibility at destination to perform a manual landing. To fly manually we normally use the autopilot disengage switch on the control wheel, and not the disengage bar on the photo. 

Hope you had a great weekend 👩‍✈️!

Guess who is starring in the latest Ad of the Today Fit App 😁? Check it out; we had a lot of fun shooting it! 

I have been using the different training options of Today Fit App for months already. I train with them in their free (!) bootcamp classes in Tamar Park in Hong Kong, and train in their Dragonboat Team. 

I also tried out the in person and online personal trainer services that @todayfitapphk offers. On my long and isolated trips, up to 10 days without option to workout outside of my hotelroom, I would normally lose quite some strength. Training with a personal trainer via the Today Fit App has boosted my motivation to train on layovers, getting workouts in designed especially for my wishes and goals. 

‘If not today, then when?’ 🏃‍♀️🏋️‍♀️💪

Use code ‘Eva10’ for 10% discount on any of the membership options. Download the App (for free!) and check out the different options to start your fitness journey :)! - Also make sure to follow @todayfitapphk 😄

node.text:
Birthday girl alert! 27 🥳 (I tried to write 36 but failed somehow 🙃)

As for many, this year has been one of reflection. Much about the future feels unstable and uncertain. The past year, due to the border restrictions, I did not see my family at all. I miss them tremendously. I had many days alone, isolated in hotelrooms. But it was also the year I was worried to lose my job, but didn’t, and still had a busy flying schedule. It was also the year of many friendships and moments of togetherness in Hong Kong. And of trying out a lot of new things and finding new communities: rock climbing, beach tennis, dragon boating, bootcamp. It was the year where my boyfriend reinvented himself, when traveling had stopped, from a travelguide to a drama teacher. Our busy lives together in Hong Kong in sharp contrast with my life alone ‘on the road ✈️’.

My heart always feels a bit heavy when it’s my birthday ☺️ But here is to celebrating the 365 days ahead 💃🥳 Taking things as they come, with gratitude and a positive attitude, and feeling blessed with many things: Brian, my partner in this adventure called life, my health, flying, the joy I find in many things, and certainly the people around me - you mean the world to me ❤️

PS Incredible how, well before I put this birthday post up, birthday DMs were coming in from those who only know me here virtually! Thank you, IG community, for your sweet support, and for keeping a sharp calendar 😜!!

node.text:
“The rudder pedals should be adjusted so that it is possible to apply maximum braking with full rudder deflection.” - In my case, (being not that tall for a Dutchie 🤷‍♀️), I use the handle on photo 2 to wind the pedals back. If a tall person flies in the same seat next, I might get a comment like this one 😆

Before you ask: I am 168 cm/5’6, so not that short; there are definitely shorter pilots operating the B747. I often get the question what the minimum height is to operate the B747, or any other jet. Some airlines set a certain height requirement for pilot candidates, but there is officially no minimum (or maximum) height specified. What is a requirement is that a pilot has to be able to reach and functionally operate all cockpit controls.

That little black strip next to me is a tool we use for optimum eye reference for operating, by adjusting the seat position. In cruise we can adjust the seat as we like, but in critical flight phases such as the landing, it is important to keep an optimized field of view. And that is what that little strip is for: to align with the eye reference point 🤓

Also thanks a lot @randolphusa for gifting me these sunglasses 🕶 Tried, tested ✈️, love them!

My latest article on my blog gives you lots of insights in the cadet pilot assessment for a flight school, and how you can prepare for it. I reviewed an extensive online preparation package, created for Ab-Initio/Cadet Pilots, designed to cover everything you may come across during the flight academy recruitment process. 

I don’t want to take anyone’s dream of becoming a pilot away, but a piece of advise: do your research on the job market and the state of the aviation industry, determine if it’s a risk you can take on, and consider having a plan B. If you do apply at a flight school, now or in the future: check out my article (link in bio) as it will help you to be well prepared!

node.text:
Long caption about this trip, but first let’s acknowledge this stunning photo of our departure from Portland - thank you @gfontana767! I love aviation photography like this, and had never dreamed of having a picture like this, where I am operating the plane myself. It’s a very precious gift. 

But the flight itself, now an event so beautifully captured on this photo, was a special one as well. This photo symbolizes for me the sense of relief and joy my colleagues and myself experienced on this particular flight. 

To be honest, I am writing this from New York (isolated in the hotel); I had the weirdest, and dare I say - taboo for flight crew! - stressful trip so far. I left Hong Kong for a 10 day trip flying to different destinations within the USA, doing the required room isolation on all my layovers. But once on this side of the world, we got heads up that Hong Kong had decided to tighten the border policy for travellers again - and possibly for air crew as well. It was unclear and pending for several days if upon my return to Hong Kong, I had to go straight to a quarantine hotel for several weeks. I was very worried about this possible prospect. I could not imagine that instead of doing my test and then returning to my partner and friends and the freedom to move around, I would return to see the walls of another hotelroom; not for days, but for weeks.. This occupied my mind a lot, for days in a row. 

Then, just before our departure from Los Angeles, via Portland 📸, to Anchorage, we got the official news that we do not have to go to quarantine after our trip. You can not imagine the weight that fell off our shoulders and with what relief and joy we operated our flights that day.

This is not to start a political discussion about rules, regulations and decisions; this is a sensitive topic. This is just me, sharing my personal experience, as I always do here. Not just showing the happy pilot peeking out of the flight deck hatch, but also some insights behind the scenes. 

Signing off from New York, operating to Hong Kong tonight, which is the last flight of this trip. Thank you for following along 🤍
